title: Aust bonds firmer after weak US data
text:
Tue, Aug 18, 2015, 10:17 AM AEST - Australia Markets close in 5 hrs 43 mins Aust bonds firmer after weak US data AAP â€“ 1 hour 0 minutes ago Recommend Print 
The Australian bond market is slightly firmer after the release of some weak US manufacturing data. 
The Empire State Manufacturing Survey showed that manufacturing activity in New York state in August plunged to its weakest level in six years. 
National Australia Bank global co-head of FX strategy Ray Attrill said the figures encouraged a move into safe-haven assets. 
"Details were not particularly promising, and will raise fresh concerns about a US manufacturing sector suffering from a high US dollar and falling oil-industry capital expenditure," he said. 
"The data has left US Treasury yields slightly lower (prices higher)." 
Mr Attrill said market reaction to the manufacturing data was limited because there were also some encouraging US housing data figures overnight. 
NAHB (Homebuilders) survey showed that confidence among US home builders was at a nine-year high. 
At 0830 AEST on Tuesday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.210 (implying a yield of 2.790 per cent), up from 97.185 (2.815 per cent) on Monday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.030 (1.970 per cent), up from 98.020 (1.980 per cent). 
In local trade on Tuesday, the market will look to the release of the minutes of the Reserve Bank's August board meeting. 
The RBA has kept the cash rate unchanged at a record low of two per cent for the past three months and traders will be keen to see if the bank is done with its interest rate cuts. 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.942pct, level with the local close on Monday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.861pct, level
